  "prompt": "When I eat sushi, what is the eel sauce made of?",
  "response": "Eel sauce, often served with sushi, is typically made from a combination of soy sauce, mirin (a sweet rice wine), and sugar. The ingredients are cooked together until they reduce and thicken into a syrupy sauce. While the name suggests a connection to eel, the sauce itself does not contain eel; it is primarily used to complement the flavors of grilled or cooked fish, including unagi (grilled eel) in sushi. Some variations of eel sauce may incorporate additional ingredients, such as sake or various spices, but the basic components remain consistent.",
